cb4add0b-4fff-4c50-adfd-295301f9edb4.3b422390-caf1-459e-aed7-cbeaad63c9b9.description=
Uses WMI to attempt to create a remote process on a machine.  The command passed should be formatted as though it was run on the command line.

CAUTION\: internally 'cmd /c' gets prepended to the command passed.  Also '2>tempfile 1>tempfile' get appended to the command so that we can attempt to capture stdout and stderr.
So your command will look like this when executed\:
	'cmd /c [your command] 2>temperr 1>tempout'
If you redirected your command yourself we will only prepend 'cmd /c' to the command.  Also by doing this we will not retrieve any results for you.

Input Parameters\:
host - hostname or ip address of the target machine
command - the command you want executed
currentDirectory - the directory to run the command from (leave blank for WMI default)
user - alternate credentials username (domain\user or remotemachine\user)
password - alternate credentials password

Responses\:
success - remote process successfully launched and has completed executing
failure - unable to start remote process

Extra Results\:
ReturnValue - return value from WMI for starting the process (not the exit value of the process)
ProcessID - the process id of the remote process
StdOut - standard output from the remote process
StdErr - standard error from the remote process

cb4add0b-4fff-4c50-adfd-295301f9edb4.db3d1f63-2892-4d22-a810-ee838a6d15b7.description=

Displays a message to the user.

Inputs\:
  message - The message text to display
  title - The title on the message window. Defaults to "Status message".

Responses\:
  Always returns success.

Examples\:
  In order to display the message "Finished" to the user, go to the 
  detail screen for the input named "message" and change the Otherwise option
  from Prompt User to Use Constant.  Then enter the text "Finished" into the
  Constant Value field.

  References to flow variables in the Contant Value field are expanded so that
  the text may be dynamic.  Flow variable references are of the form
  ${variable}.  For example, the text\:
     ${count} systems were modified 
  could be used to display a message about the number of systems that were
  repaired, whose value is in the flow variable "count".

  When the message is displayed, it will properly render any embedded html
  tags, which permits creating messages with more advanced formatting.  For 
  example to display a message in italics you could use\:
    This is important
  or to display a message in red\:
    This is really  important

  You can create messages that contain multiple lines by entering a multiple
  line message in the Constant Value field, or by using HTML 
 tags for line
  breaks.  Note that \n characters are displayed literally and are not used for
  creating multiple lines.
